<subSubSection box="[151,668,1366,1392]" pageId="16" pageNumber="317" type="nomenclature">
<paragraph blockId="16.[151,668,1366,1392]" box="[151,668,1366,1392]" pageId="16" pageNumber="317">
<heading bold="true" box="[151,668,1366,1392]" fontSize="11" level="1" pageId="16" pageNumber="317" reason="1">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,668,1366,1392]" pageId="16" pageNumber="317">
Subfamily 
<taxonomicName authority="Kobayashi, 1960" authorityName="Kobayashi" authorityYear="1960" box="[287,668,1366,1392]" class="Trilobita" family="Asaphidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Asaphida" pageId="16" pageNumber="317" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Birmanitinae">
Birmanitinae 
<bibRefCitation author="Kobayashi, T." box="[461,668,1366,1392]" pageId="16" pageNumber="317" pagination="217 - 275" refId="ref45125" refString="Kobayashi, T. (1960) The Cambro-Ordovician formations and faunas of South Korea, part 6, Paleontology V. Journal of the Faculty of Sciences, University of Tokyo, Section 2, 12 (2), 217 - 275." type="journal article" year="1960">Kobayashi, 1960</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="17" lastPageNumber="318" pageId="16" pageNumber="317" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="16.[151,1437,1438,2041]" pageId="16" pageNumber="317">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,284,1438,1464]" pageId="16" pageNumber="317">Discussion.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authority="Sheng, 1934" authorityName="Sheng" authorityYear="1934" box="[292,566,1439,1465]" class="Trilobita" family="Asaphidae" genus="Birmanites" kingdom="Animalia" order="Asaphida" pageId="16" pageNumber="317" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[292,415,1439,1464]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="317">Birmanites</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Sheng, X. - F." box="[422,566,1439,1465]" pageId="16" pageNumber="317" pagination="1 - 19" refId="ref47171" refString="Sheng, X. - F. (1934) Lower Ordovician faunas of Chekiang. Palaeontologica Sinica New Series, 3, 1 - 19." type="journal article" year="1934">Sheng, 1934</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, with 
<typeStatus box="[634,682,1439,1465]" pageId="16" pageNumber="317">type</typeStatus>
species 
<taxonomicName authority="Reed, 1915" authorityName="Reed" authorityYear="1915" box="[778,1150,1438,1465]" class="Trilobita" family="Asaphidae" genus="Ogygites" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Asaphida" pageId="16" pageNumber="317" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="birmanicus">
<emphasis box="[778,1011,1439,1465]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="317">Ogygites birmanicus</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Reed, F. R. C." box="[1019,1150,1438,1465]" pageId="16" pageNumber="317" pagination="1 - 98" refId="ref46807" refString="Reed, F. R. C. (1915) Supplementary Memoir on new Ordovician and Silurian fossils from the Northern Shan States. Palaeontologia Indica, New Series 6, 1 - 98." type="book chapter" year="1915">Reed, 1915</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, was originally described as an asaphid, but was placed in a separate family 
<taxonomicName box="[729,875,1475,1501]" family="Birmanitidae" pageId="16" pageNumber="317" rank="family">Birmanitidae</taxonomicName>
by 
<bibRefCitation author="Kobayashi, T." box="[920,1116,1475,1501]" pageId="16" pageNumber="317" pagination="217 - 275" refId="ref45125" refString="Kobayashi, T. (1960) The Cambro-Ordovician formations and faunas of South Korea, part 6, Paleontology V. Journal of the Faculty of Sciences, University of Tokyo, Section 2, 12 (2), 217 - 275." type="journal article" year="1960">Kobayashi (1960</bibRefCitation>
, p. 254) and in 
<taxonomicName class="Trilobita" family="Dikelokephalinidae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Asaphida" pageId="16" pageNumber="317" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Dikelokephalinidae</taxonomicName>
in the 1959 
<emphasis box="[378,801,1511,1537]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="317">Treatise on Invertebrate Paleontology</emphasis>
(Harrington 
<emphasis box="[947,1031,1511,1537]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="317">et al. in</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Moore, R. C." box="[1037,1185,1510,1537]" pageId="16" pageNumber="317" refId="ref46007" refString="Moore, R. C. (Ed.) (1959) Treatise on Invertebrate Paleontology - Arthropoda 1. University of Kansas Press and the Geological Society of America, Lawrence, Kansas, 560 pp." type="book" year="1959">Moore, 1959</bibRefCitation>
). 
<bibRefCitation author="Lu, Y. - H." box="[1204,1309,1510,1537]" pageId="16" pageNumber="317" pagination="1 - 453" refId="ref45640" refString="Lu, Y. - H. (1975) Ordovician trilobite faunas of central and southwestern China. Palaeontologia Sinica, New Series B, 11, 1 - 453." type="journal article" year="1975">Lu (1975</bibRefCitation>
, p. 319) regarded 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Sheng" authorityYear="1934" box="[233,356,1547,1572]" class="Trilobita" family="Asaphidae" genus="Birmanites" kingdom="Animalia" order="Asaphida" pageId="16" pageNumber="317" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[233,356,1547,1572]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="317">Birmanites</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
as no more than an unusually flat asaphid, with a relatively small glabella, an opinion with which we concur; the taxon 
<taxonomicName box="[393,539,1583,1609]" family="Birmanitidae" pageId="16" pageNumber="317" rank="family">Birmanitidae</taxonomicName>
has disappeared from the literature. It is, however, still available as a subfamily name within 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Salter" authorityYear="1864" box="[298,420,1619,1645]" class="Trilobita" family="Asaphidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Asaphida" pageId="16" pageNumber="317" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Asaphidae</taxonomicName>
. Division of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Salter" authorityYear="1864" box="[566,684,1619,1645]" class="Trilobita" family="Asaphidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Asaphida" pageId="16" pageNumber="317" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Asaphidae</taxonomicName>
into subfamilies is itself contentious; a relatively conservative approach was used by Jaanusson (
<emphasis box="[505,527,1655,1680]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="317">in</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Moore, R. C." box="[533,682,1654,1681]" pageId="16" pageNumber="317" refId="ref46007" refString="Moore, R. C. (Ed.) (1959) Treatise on Invertebrate Paleontology - Arthropoda 1. University of Kansas Press and the Geological Society of America, Lawrence, Kansas, 560 pp." type="book" year="1959">Moore, 1959</bibRefCitation>
), who employed seven subfamilies. The opposite approach was that of 
<bibRefCitation author="Balashova, E. A." box="[181,379,1691,1717]" pageId="16" pageNumber="317" refId="ref42554" refString="Balashova, E. A. (1976) Systematics of asaphine trilobites and their representatives in the USSR. Nedra, Leningrad, 215 pp. [in Russian]" type="book" year="1976">Balashova (1976)</bibRefCitation>
who elevated 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Salter" authorityYear="1864" box="[540,658,1691,1717]" class="Trilobita" family="Asaphidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Asaphida" pageId="16" pageNumber="317" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Asaphidae</taxonomicName>
to subordinal level and divided the group into numerous families and subfamilies. Balashova nominated subfamilies centred on well-known Baltic endemic genera such as 
<taxonomicName authority="Jaanuson, 1956" authorityName="Jaanuson" authorityYear="1956" class="Trilobita" family="Asaphidae" genus="Megistaspis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Asaphida" pageId="16" pageNumber="317" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1302,1436,1727,1752]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="317">Megistaspis</emphasis>
Jaanuson, 1956
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authority="Schmidt, 1901" authorityName="Schmidt" authorityYear="1901" box="[340,687,1763,1789]" class="Trilobita" family="Asaphidae" genus="Pseudoasaphus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Asaphida" pageId="16" pageNumber="317" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[340,514,1763,1789]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="317">Pseudoasaphus</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Schmidt, F." box="[523,687,1763,1789]" pageId="16" pageNumber="317" pagination="1 - 113" refId="ref47064" refString="Schmidt, F. (1901) Revision der Ostbaltischen Silurischen Trilobiten. Abtheilung V: Asaphiden. Lieferung 2. Die Gattungen Asaphus sens. str., Onchometopus, Isotelus und Niobe enthaltend. Memoires de l'Academie Imperiale des Sciences de St. Petersbourg, Series 8, 12 (8), 1 - 113." type="journal article" year="1901">Schmidt, 1901</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="Angelin, 1854" authorityName="Angelin" authorityYear="1854" box="[744,1046,1762,1789]" class="Trilobita" family="Asaphidae" genus="Ptychopyge" kingdom="Animalia" order="Asaphida" pageId="16" pageNumber="317" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[744,875,1763,1789]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="317">Ptychopyge</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Angelin, N. P." box="[882,1046,1762,1789]" pageId="16" pageNumber="317" pagination="21 - 92" refId="ref42322" refString="Angelin, N. P. (1854) s. n. In: Palaeontologia Scandinavica I. Crustacea Formationis Transitionis Fasc. 2. Academiae Regiae Scientarum Suecanae, Holmiae, pp. 21 - 92." type="book chapter" year="1854">Angelin, 1854</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, to each of which she consigned a number of her own, finely divided genera. This is not an appropriate place to review this work of prolific taxonomic ‘splitting’, although the majority of Balashova’s taxa are confined to the Ordovician Baltic Shield, and her scheme has not been widely adopted. However, 
<bibRefCitation author="Balashova, E. A." box="[602,819,1871,1897]" pageId="16" pageNumber="317" refId="ref42554" refString="Balashova, E. A. (1976) Systematics of asaphine trilobites and their representatives in the USSR. Nedra, Leningrad, 215 pp. [in Russian]" type="book" year="1976">Balashova’s (1976)</bibRefCitation>
Subfamily 
<taxonomicName box="[951,1133,1871,1897]" pageId="16" pageNumber="317" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Nobiliasaphinae">Nobiliasaphinae</taxonomicName>
(placed in Family 
<taxonomicName authority="Balashova, 1969" authorityName="Balashova" authorityYear="1969" family="Pseudoasaphidae" pageId="16" pageNumber="317" rank="family">
Pseudoasaphidae 
<bibRefCitation author="Balashova, E. A." box="[268,458,1907,1933]" pageId="16" pageNumber="317" pagination="31 - 41" refId="ref42515" refString="Balashova, E. A. (1969) Phylogeny of trilobites in the Subfamily Pseudoasaphinae. Vestnik Leningradskogo Universiteta, Series Geology, Geography, 1969 (4), 31 - 41. [in Russian]" type="journal article" year="1969">Balashova, 1969</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, by 
<bibRefCitation author="Balashova, E. A." box="[504,703,1907,1933]" pageId="16" pageNumber="317" refId="ref42554" refString="Balashova, E. A. (1976) Systematics of asaphine trilobites and their representatives in the USSR. Nedra, Leningrad, 215 pp. [in Russian]" type="book" year="1976">Balashova [1976]</bibRefCitation>
) includes the genera 
<taxonomicName authority="Kielan, 1960" authorityName="Kielan" authorityYear="1960" box="[941,1260,1907,1933]" class="Trilobita" family="Asaphidae" genus="Opsimasaphus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Asaphida" pageId="16" pageNumber="317" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[941,1106,1907,1933]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="317">Opsimasaphus</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Kielan, Z." box="[1112,1260,1907,1933]" pageId="16" pageNumber="317" pagination="1 - 191" refId="ref44947" refString="Kielan, Z. (1960) Upper Ordovician trilobites from Poland and some related forms from Bohemia and Scandinavia. Acta Palaeontologica Polonica, 11, 1 - 191." type="journal article" year="1960">Kielan, 1960</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, and 
<taxonomicName authority="Pribyl &amp; Vanek, 1965" authorityName="Pribyl &amp; Vanek" authorityYear="1965" class="Trilobita" family="Asaphidae" genus="Nobiliasaphus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Asaphida" pageId="16" pageNumber="317" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="317">Nobiliasaphus</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Pribyl, A. &amp; Vanek, J." box="[211,456,1942,1969]" pageId="16" pageNumber="317" pagination="277 - 282" refId="ref46547" refString="Pribyl, A. &amp; Vanek, J. (1965) Neue Trilobiten des bohmischen Ordoviziums. Vestnik Ustredniho Ustavu Geologickeho, 40, 277 - 282." type="journal article" year="1965">Přibyl &amp; Vaněk, 1965</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, both of which are closely similar to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Sheng" authorityYear="1934" box="[868,991,1943,1968]" class="Trilobita" family="Asaphidae" genus="Birmanites" kingdom="Animalia" order="Asaphida" pageId="16" pageNumber="317" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[868,991,1943,1968]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="317">Birmanites</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, and must surely be included within the same subfamily, whatever taxonomy is eventually adopted. The name 
<taxonomicName authority="Kobayashi, 1960" authorityName="Kobayashi" authorityYear="1960" box="[953,1300,1979,2005]" class="Trilobita" family="Asaphidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Asaphida" pageId="16" pageNumber="317" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Birmanitinae">
Birmanitinae 
<bibRefCitation author="Kobayashi, T." box="[1108,1300,1979,2005]" pageId="16" pageNumber="317" pagination="217 - 275" refId="ref45125" refString="Kobayashi, T. (1960) The Cambro-Ordovician formations and faunas of South Korea, part 6, Paleontology V. Journal of the Faculty of Sciences, University of Tokyo, Section 2, 12 (2), 217 - 275." type="journal article" year="1960">Kobayashi, 1960</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
is the older name for this group even though it was not recognised by 
<bibRefCitation author="Balashova, E. A." box="[802,1003,2015,2041]" pageId="16" pageNumber="317" refId="ref42554" refString="Balashova, E. A. (1976) Systematics of asaphine trilobites and their representatives in the USSR. Nedra, Leningrad, 215 pp. [in Russian]" type="book" year="1976">Balashova (1976)</bibRefCitation>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="17.[151,1437,151,1257]" pageId="17" pageNumber="318">
An objective appraisal of asaphid trilobites is overdue. An unpublished PhD thesis by Mark 
<bibRefCitation author="Bell, M. A." box="[1236,1365,151,177]" pageId="17" pageNumber="318" refId="ref42650" refString="Bell, M. A. (2009) Macroevolutionary patterns of body-size evolution within the Class Trilobita (Arthropoda). Unpublished PhD thesis, University of Bristol, Bristol. [unknown pagination]" type="book" year="2009">Bell (2009)</bibRefCitation>
under the supervision of RAF attempted a cladistic analysis of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Salter" authorityYear="1864" box="[783,905,187,213]" class="Trilobita" family="Asaphidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Asaphida" pageId="17" pageNumber="318" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Asaphidae</taxonomicName>
. One group that comprised a clade with moderate support included 
<emphasis box="[392,522,223,248]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="318">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Sheng" authorityYear="1934" box="[392,518,223,248]" class="Trilobita" family="Asaphidae" genus="Birmanites" kingdom="Animalia" order="Asaphida" pageId="17" pageNumber="318" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Birmanites</taxonomicName>
,
</emphasis>
and the name 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Kobayashi" authorityYear="1960" box="[694,840,223,249]" class="Trilobita" family="Asaphidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Asaphida" pageId="17" pageNumber="326" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Birmanitinae">Birmanitinae</taxonomicName>
is appropriate for it. The most important characters uniting the group are displayed by the hypostome, which has a characteristic rounded to oval middle body with prominent maculae at the rear, and a broad, U-shaped fork, and hypostome widest at, or in front of the maculae. The characteristic hypostome is illustrated by a specimen from the type series of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Reed" baseAuthorityYear="1915" box="[1014,1270,331,357]" class="Trilobita" family="Asaphidae" genus="Birmanites" kingdom="Animalia" order="Asaphida" pageId="17" pageNumber="318" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="birmanicus">
<emphasis box="[1014,1270,331,357]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="318">Birmanites birmanicus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
figured herein (
<figureCitation box="[159,250,367,393]" captionStart="FIGURE 6" captionStartId="19.[151,250,1801,1825]" captionTargetBox="[199,1388,181,1777]" captionTargetId="figure-18@19.[199,1388,181,1777]" captionTargetPageId="19" captionText="FIGURE 6. Birmanites birmanicus (Reed) from the Hwe Mawng Beds (uppermost Katian), northern Shan State, Myanmar. 1. Hypostome (original of Reed 1915, pl. 5, fig. 17), GSI 11519, Hwe Mawng. 2a, b. Cephalon (original of Reed 1915, pl. 6, fig. 2), GSI 11522, Hwe Mawng, original and retrodeformation. 3. Partial specimen (original of Reed 1915, pl. 6, fig. 3), GSI 11523, Hpakhi. 4a, b. Pygidium (original of Reed 1915, pl. 6, fig. 4), GSI 11524, Hwe Mawng, original and retrodeformation. 5. Cranidium (original of Reed 1915, pl. 7, fig. 2), GSI 11534, Hpakhi. 6. Partial specimen (original of Reed 1915, pl. 5, figs 15,16), GSI 11518, Hpakhi. Scale bars = 2 mm for 1; = 5 mm for 2–6." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6810306" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6810306/files/figure.png" pageId="17" pageNumber="318">Fig. 6.1</figureCitation>
) and an illustrative reconstruction (
<figureCitation box="[657,748,367,393]" captionStart="FIGURE 7" captionStartId="20.[151,250,1662,1686]" captionTargetBox="[368,1218,489,1639]" captionTargetId="figure-188@20.[368,1219,489,1639]" captionTargetPageId="20" captionText="FIGURE 7. Reconstruction of Birmanites birmanicus (Reed). A) Dorsal skeleton; B) Hypostome." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6810310" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6810310/files/figure.png" pageId="17" pageNumber="318">Fig. 7.b</figureCitation>
), and by the Barrandian 
<typeStatus box="[1033,1136,367,393]" pageId="17" pageNumber="318">lectotype</typeStatus>
(selected 
<bibRefCitation author="Kielan, Z." box="[1253,1402,367,393]" pageId="17" pageNumber="318" pagination="1 - 191" refId="ref44947" refString="Kielan, Z. (1960) Upper Ordovician trilobites from Poland and some related forms from Bohemia and Scandinavia. Acta Palaeontologica Polonica, 11, 1 - 191." type="journal article" year="1960">Kielan, 1960</bibRefCitation>
, p. 76) of 
<taxonomicName box="[226,470,403,429]" class="Trilobita" family="Asaphidae" genus="Nobiliasaphus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Asaphida" pageId="17" pageNumber="318" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nobilis">
<emphasis box="[226,470,403,429]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="318">Nobiliasaphus nobilis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(see 
<bibRefCitation author="Horny, R. &amp; Bastl, F." box="[529,767,403,429]" pageId="17" pageNumber="318" refId="ref44590" refString="Horny, R. &amp; Bastl, F. (1970) Type specimen of fossils in the National Museum, Prague. Trilobita. National Museum, Prague, Prague, 354 pp." type="book" year="1970">Horný &amp; Bastl, 1970</bibRefCitation>
, pl. 6 fig. 1; 
<bibRefCitation author="Rabano, I." box="[908,1067,403,429]" pageId="17" pageNumber="318" pagination="541 - 609" refId="ref46614" refString="Rabano, I. (1989) Trilobites del Ordovicico Medio del sector meridional de la Zona Centroiberica espanola. Part II Agnostina y Asaphida Publicaciones Especiales del Boletin Geologico y Minero, 100, 541 - 609." type="journal article" year="1989">Rabáno, 1989</bibRefCitation>
, pl. 3, fig. 6; also, 
<bibRefCitation author="Hughes, C. P." box="[1274,1432,403,429]" pageId="17" pageNumber="318" pagination="109 - 181" refId="ref44696" refString="Hughes, C. P. (1979) The Ordovician trilobite faunas of the Builth-Llandrindod Inlier, central Wales. Part 3. Bulletin of the British Museum (Natural History) Geology Series, 32, 109 - 181." type="journal article" year="1979">Hughes, 1979</bibRefCitation>
, fig. 11 for a similar hypostome, and 
<bibRefCitation author="Hammann, W. &amp; Leone, F." box="[559,848,439,465]" pageId="17" pageNumber="318" pagination="1 - 217" refId="ref44454" refString="Hammann, W. &amp; Leone, F. (1997) Trilobites from the post-Sardic (Upper Ordovician) sequence of southern Sardinia. Part 1. Beringeria, 20, 1 - 217." type="journal article" year="1997">Hammann &amp; Leone 1997</bibRefCitation>
, pl. 6, fig. 3 and 
<bibRefCitation author="Turvey, S. T." box="[1036,1184,439,465]" pageId="17" pageNumber="318" pagination="347 - 399" refId="ref48057" refString="Turvey, S. T. (2007) Asaphoid trilobites from the Arenig-Llanvirn of the South China Plate. Palaeontology, 50, 347 - 399. https: // doi. org / 10.1111 / j. 1475 - 4983.2006.00641. x" type="journal article" year="2007">Turvey, 2007</bibRefCitation>
for further examples). Dorsal characters in the group are variable with regard to width of pleural areas, preglabellar field, dorsal effacement and the like, but a glabella with an inflated, often pyriform frontal lobe and with a pair of posteriorly inwardly sloping, and often deepened axial/glabellar furrows which constrict a narrow median glabellar lobe in front of the occipital ring, is also typical. Where known, the medial tubercle is immediately pre-occipital (
<taxonomicName authorityName="Sheng" authorityYear="1934" box="[1205,1328,583,608]" class="Trilobita" family="Asaphidae" genus="Birmanites" kingdom="Animalia" order="Asaphida" pageId="17" pageNumber="318" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1205,1328,583,608]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="318">Birmanites</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
—see 
<bibRefCitation author="Lu, Y. - H." pageId="17" pageNumber="318" pagination="1 - 453" refId="ref45640" refString="Lu, Y. - H. (1975) Ordovician trilobite faunas of central and southwestern China. Palaeontologia Sinica, New Series B, 11, 1 - 453." type="journal article" year="1975">Lu, 1975</bibRefCitation>
, pl. 8, fig. 8), and the dorsal facial sutures run at, or at least very close to the anterior margin before they meet medially. A distinctive genus from central 
<collectingCountry box="[621,727,655,681]" name="Australia" pageId="17" pageNumber="318">Australia</collectingCountry>
, 
<taxonomicName authority="Fortey &amp; Shergold, 1984" authorityName="Fortey &amp; Shergold" authorityYear="1984" box="[738,1160,655,681]" class="Trilobita" genus="Norasaphus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Asaphida" pageId="17" pageNumber="318" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[738,873,655,681]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="318">Norasaphus</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Fortey, R. A. &amp; Shergold, J. H." box="[879,1160,655,681]" pageId="17" pageNumber="318" pagination="315 - 366" refId="ref44152" refString="Fortey, R. A. &amp; Shergold, J. H. (1984) Early Ordovician trilobites, Nora Formation, central Australia. Palaeontology, 27, 315 - 366." type="journal article" year="1984">Fortey &amp; Shergold, 1984</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, which includes the only tuberculate asaphids, also belongs within the same group, showing similar hypostome construction and glabella furrows, even though it is much more convex and less flattened peripherally than 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Sheng" authorityYear="1934" box="[1065,1188,727,752]" class="Trilobita" family="Asaphidae" genus="Birmanites" kingdom="Animalia" order="Asaphida" pageId="17" pageNumber="318" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1065,1188,727,752]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="318">Birmanites</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. 
<bibRefCitation author="Turvey, S. T." box="[1201,1363,727,753]" pageId="17" pageNumber="318" pagination="347 - 399" refId="ref48057" refString="Turvey, S. T. (2007) Asaphoid trilobites from the Arenig-Llanvirn of the South China Plate. Palaeontology, 50, 347 - 399. https: // doi. org / 10.1111 / j. 1475 - 4983.2006.00641. x" type="journal article" year="2007">Turvey (2007)</bibRefCitation>
added further Chinese taxa to this group. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Pribyl &amp; Vanek" authorityYear="1965" box="[542,704,763,789]" class="Trilobita" family="Asaphidae" genus="Nobiliasaphus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Asaphida" pageId="17" pageNumber="318" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[542,704,763,789]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="318">Nobiliasaphus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is distinguished from 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Sheng" authorityYear="1934" box="[956,1079,763,788]" class="Trilobita" family="Asaphidae" genus="Birmanites" kingdom="Animalia" order="Asaphida" pageId="17" pageNumber="318" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[956,1079,763,788]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="318">Birmanites</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in having a curious structure of the pygidial axis, with chevron-like medial backward deflections of the ring furrows, the ring itself bisected transversely by fainter extra furrows and ridges of similar form.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="17.[151,1437,151,1257]" pageId="17" pageNumber="318">
This asaphid group is peri-Gondwanan, with scattered occurrences from 
<collectingCountry box="[1025,1104,871,897]" name="France" pageId="17" pageNumber="318">France</collectingCountry>
, Iberian Peninsula and 
<collectingCountry box="[1368,1436,871,897]" name="United Kingdom" pageId="17" pageNumber="318">Wales</collectingCountry>
eastwards to southwest 
<collectingCountry box="[416,487,907,933]" name="China" pageId="17" pageNumber="318">China</collectingCountry>
. The genus 
<emphasis box="[620,796,907,933]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="318">Pamirotetchites</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Balashova, E. A." box="[803,993,907,933]" pageId="17" pageNumber="318" pagination="191 - 263" refId="ref42474" refString="Balashova, E. A. (1966) Trilobites from the Ordovician and Silurian beds of Pamir. Trudy Upravlenya Geologii Soveta Ministrov Tadzhikskoi SSR. Paleontologiya I Stratigrafiya, 2, 191 - 263. [in Russian]" type="journal article" year="1966">Balashova, 1966</bibRefCitation>
, from the Pamirs in central Asia is a junior synonym of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Pribyl &amp; Vanek" authorityYear="1965" box="[339,501,943,969]" class="Trilobita" family="Asaphidae" genus="Nobiliasaphus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Asaphida" pageId="17" pageNumber="318" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[339,501,943,969]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="318">Nobiliasaphus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
as 
<bibRefCitation author="Balashova, E. A." box="[536,727,943,969]" pageId="17" pageNumber="318" refId="ref42554" refString="Balashova, E. A. (1976) Systematics of asaphine trilobites and their representatives in the USSR. Nedra, Leningrad, 215 pp. [in Russian]" type="book" year="1976">Balashova (1976</bibRefCitation>
, p. 59) realised, and displays the same distinctive pygidial structure as 
<taxonomicName authority="(Barrande)" baseAuthorityName="Barrande" box="[232,470,979,1005]" class="Trilobita" family="Asaphidae" genus="Nobiliasaphus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Asaphida" pageId="17" pageNumber="318" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nobilis">
<emphasis box="[232,341,979,1005]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="318">N. nobilis</emphasis>
(Barrande)
</taxonomicName>
(see also 
<taxonomicName authority="Lu, 1975" authorityName="Lu" authorityYear="1975" box="[581,1064,978,1005]" class="Trilobita" family="Asaphidae" genus="Opsimasaphus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Asaphida" pageId="17" pageNumber="318" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pseudodawanicus">
<emphasis box="[581,952,979,1005]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="318">Opsimasaphus pseudodawanicus</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Lu, Y. - H." box="[960,1064,978,1005]" pageId="17" pageNumber="318" pagination="1 - 453" refId="ref45640" refString="Lu, Y. - H. (1975) Ordovician trilobite faunas of central and southwestern China. Palaeontologia Sinica, New Series B, 11, 1 - 453." type="journal article" year="1975">Lu, 1975</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<emphasis box="[1075,1097,979,1004]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="318">in</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Turvey, S. T." box="[1103,1257,979,1005]" pageId="17" pageNumber="318" pagination="347 - 399" refId="ref48057" refString="Turvey, S. T. (2007) Asaphoid trilobites from the Arenig-Llanvirn of the South China Plate. Palaeontology, 50, 347 - 399. https: // doi. org / 10.1111 / j. 1475 - 4983.2006.00641. x" type="journal article" year="2007">Turvey, 2007</bibRefCitation>
). 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Fortey &amp; Shergold" authorityYear="1984" box="[1275,1410,979,1005]" class="Trilobita" genus="Norasaphus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Asaphida" pageId="17" pageNumber="318" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1275,1410,979,1005]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="318">Norasaphus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is so far confined to 
<collectingCountry box="[348,454,1015,1041]" name="Australia" pageId="17" pageNumber="318">Australia</collectingCountry>
, while 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Pribyl &amp; Vanek" authorityYear="1965" box="[531,693,1015,1041]" class="Trilobita" family="Asaphidae" genus="Nobiliasaphus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Asaphida" pageId="17" pageNumber="318" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[531,693,1015,1041]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="318">Nobiliasaphus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
does not extend east of the Pamirs. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Sheng" authorityYear="1934" box="[1086,1209,1015,1040]" class="Trilobita" family="Asaphidae" genus="Birmanites" kingdom="Animalia" order="Asaphida" pageId="17" pageNumber="318" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1086,1209,1015,1040]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="318">Birmanites</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is more widespread. Whether this group should be included within a more inclusive clade based on 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Schmidt" authorityYear="1901" box="[1036,1210,1051,1077]" class="Trilobita" family="Asaphidae" genus="Pseudoasaphus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Asaphida" pageId="17" pageNumber="318" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1036,1210,1051,1077]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="318">Pseudoasaphus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(as claimed by 
<bibRefCitation author="Balashova, E. A." pageId="17" pageNumber="318" refId="ref42554" refString="Balashova, E. A. (1976) Systematics of asaphine trilobites and their representatives in the USSR. Nedra, Leningrad, 215 pp. [in Russian]" type="book" year="1976">Balashova, 1976</bibRefCitation>
) is uncertain. Many genera of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Salter" authorityYear="1864" box="[643,761,1087,1113]" class="Trilobita" family="Asaphidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Asaphida" pageId="17" pageNumber="318" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Asaphidae</taxonomicName>
are known to be endemic to Baltica, such as those placed in Megistaspidinae by 
<bibRefCitation author="Balashova, E. A." box="[375,575,1123,1149]" pageId="17" pageNumber="318" refId="ref42554" refString="Balashova, E. A. (1976) Systematics of asaphine trilobites and their representatives in the USSR. Nedra, Leningrad, 215 pp. [in Russian]" type="book" year="1976">Balashova (1976)</bibRefCitation>
, and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Schmidt" authorityYear="1901" box="[633,807,1123,1149]" class="Trilobita" family="Asaphidae" genus="Pseudoasaphus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Asaphida" pageId="17" pageNumber="318" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[633,807,1123,1149]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="318">Pseudoasaphus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
may be no exception. 
<taxonomicName box="[1057,1284,1123,1149]" class="Trilobita" family="Asaphidae" genus="Pseudoasaphus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Asaphida" pageId="17" pageNumber="318" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="undetermined">
<emphasis box="[1057,1231,1123,1149]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="318">Pseudoasaphus</emphasis>
spp.
</taxonomicName>
have anterior branches of the facial sutures which cross the fontal area well away from the anterior cephalic margin before meeting in an acute point (e.g. Jaanusson, 1953, pl. 4, fig. 3), and hypostomes attributed to related genera are relatively long and narrow, with more extended ‘forks’ subtending an almost v-shaped outline (
<bibRefCitation author="Balashova, E. A." box="[1103,1294,1231,1257]" pageId="17" pageNumber="318" refId="ref42554" refString="Balashova, E. A. (1976) Systematics of asaphine trilobites and their representatives in the USSR. Nedra, Leningrad, 215 pp. [in Russian]" type="book" year="1976">Balashova, 1976</bibRefCitation>
, pl. 3).
</paragraph>
